and","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spellman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the early Middle English personal name <i>Spileman</i>, <i>Speleman</i>, late Old English <i>Spilemann</i>. Its original sense was probably ‘entertainer’ (literally ‘play-man’), corresponding to Middle High German <i>spilmann</i>, Middle Low German <i>speelman</i> (see above). However, although <i>spile</i> ‘play, sport, revelry’ and <i>spilen</i> ‘to play’ occur in Middle English, there is no evidence for a word <i>spileman</i>, and all the English evidence points to this surname being from the personal name rather than an occupational name.","Irish: in Connacht, an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Spealáin</b> and <b>Ó Spealáin</b> (see   Spillane  ).","Americanized form of German <b>Spellmann</b>: occupational name for a musician or minstrel, from Middle Low German <i>spel</i> ‘play’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."],"variants":[{"name":"Spillane","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Ciaran, Donal.","Irish (Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Spealáin</b> or <b>Ó Spealáin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Spealán</i>’, a personal name based on <i>speal</i> ‘scythe’. Compare   Smullen  ."]},{"name":"Spillman","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Spellman  .","Americanized form of German <b>Spillmann</b>: variant of   Spielmann  ."]},{"name":"Spelman","meanings":["English and Irish (Galway): variant of   Spellman   and   Spillman  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":22,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/